segments.text: This is an interview with Brigadier General Gaber Kidwell.
Today's date is 8 June 1981.
This is Terry Anderson.
This is a test in Dallas.
Okay, let's start then.
Today's interview is with Brigadier General Kidwell.
Today is June 8, 1981.
Could you first start out by telling us where and when you were born?
I was born in Dallas down on the corner of Ross and Fitchview on February the 4th, 1910.
Could you tell us about your parents?
Let's start with your father.
My father was Charles Weems Kidwell, who was born in Louisiana, moved to Texas when he was a baby in arms.
And he grew up in Dallas.
His mother brought him here as a very young widow.
Do you remember approximately when he came to Dallas?
In the 1880s or 90s?
Well, that's something I have to look up.
No, I don't.
I'm sure it was in the 1880s.
And he went to the schools here in Dallas and then attended the Ed Rand Christian College.
out of Thorpe Springs, Texas, which is the forerunner of Texas Christian University today.
And Mr. Edison Randall, a private schoolmaster, set this thing up in conjunction with some Christian church endeavors out of Thorpe Springs, which
I've been there with my father and seen the old ruins of this school.
Did it burn down or did they abandon it?
Well, I'm sure it burned down and the Christian church decided to move it to Fort Worth.
And it's long since been abandoned.
Did he have four years of college education then?
No, he did not have four years of college education.
Financial hardships entered into the picture, and he went to work for Sanger Brothers, a department store operating in Dallas and Fort Worth and in Waco.
Mr. Alex Sanger and four German immigrant brothers owned the store.
And they employed my father.
And he worked there all his life, all his adult life.
A salesman?
Well, he started out as a salesman and got to be a department head.
And then he got to be assistant manager.
And then he got to be manager of the Dallas store.
And then he got to be general superintendent of the Dallas, the Waco, and the Fort Worth stores.
At that time, it was a very responsible job.
No kidding.
When did he become general superintendent?
When about was that?
I'm sure this was in the 1925 era, somewhere in there.
I was just starting in high school.
I started high school in 1924.
So in that area.
So he was in a management or a leadership position also?
He was in management, right.
Because of his job and because he had two young sons, he was not in the World War I.
whether they drafted him in those days or whether he got exempt or what the story is.
I don't know, but he was not in the army.
Could you describe him?
What did he look like?
What kind of personality or character was he?
Well, he was very extrovert.
He loved people.
naturally loved people in his job.
He loved helping people and he was a great great civic worker and that he worked with the in those days the they called it the community chess drives.
He was a big
worker and when they built the new YMCA here in Dallas, he took up, I remember, over a half million dollars himself, by himself, back in 1931 or something like this, 30 or 31, which was some doings.
During the Depression, that's right.
Purely by his consistency and tenacity and not giving up and letting somebody say, well,
come back next week.
He stayed with them and he was recognized at a dinner they had after they got whatever amount of money, $750,000 or something like that for their efforts.
Dad was recognized for it.
Sounds like a hard worker.
Well, he was a very hard worker.
He worked six days a week.
And he played with his kids the seventh day a week.
And he was a diligent church man.
He worked in the church and was of the First Presbyterian Church down in Dallas.
And he was president of his class.
His high school clients?
No, no.
Down at the church.
Oh, OK, OK. Down at the church.
He loved to work with the kids in the neighborhood.
And in the event that was unusual, he'd gather up a whole carload of kids and take us to show it to us where there was a spectacular accident or the circus came to town.
They used to unload out here at Fair Park.
And we'd go out and watch the elephants help unload the cars and watch the parade from the fairgrounds down
downtown where they always had a circus down there by Pearl Street Market.
And he'd always get a cartload of kids and take us down there.
And he was a big worker in the baseball league.
They didn't call them little leagues in those days.
They were area leagues.
We had one in East Dallas and they had one in Oak Cliff.
They had a team in South Dallas.
And he was a sponsor there.
He sponsored a lot of work with the dads clubs at North Dallas High School.
And that's where I first became interested in army training was at North Dallas.
He encouraged me.
And I joined the junior OTCs there and stayed with it right until.
I retired in 1962.
Let's, before we start talking about that, let's talk about your mother.
Can you tell me about her?
Mama was the 11th and last child of her family.
H.W.
Graber and family.
Grandfather Graber came over from Hamburg, Germany as a young engineer.
and got off a boat down at Galveston and got a job with the old Texas Midland Railroad Company.
And he railroaded up to Milliken, where the Civil War caught him, and he joined the Texas Rangers Regiment, which was a cavalry range of foraging outfit.
And he fought four years in the Civil War.
And during this time, he established himself as a real leader of men, meaning that he led raiding parties, gathering food and horses and animals,
cows and sheep for food for the armies.
That's what they were.
They lived on the land and he was the leader of one of these foraging parties and as such he was captured twice.
And once he escaped from Union prison and then they let him out on parole on the other time.
Got tired of feeding him, I guess.
But after the war, he came back.
And in that time, he'd met a girl sometime during his, he met a girl down in Courtney, Texas, who had befriended him and helped him escape capture.
And after the war, he ended up at war over in Virginia.
He came back to Courtney, Texas, which is down below Navasota on Lombardos.
Courtney was a big...
cotton shipping town then, Port.
They called it Cotton Shipping Port.
They had a pretty good size warfare and they would haul cotton down to Courtney and put it on barges and haul it on down to Galveston.
Anyway, he married this girl who was down there visiting some of her folks and she lived in Massachusetts.
She was a Parks.
And she, they married and
He railroaded from Milliken, or whenever it was after the end of the war, Civil War, up to Waxahachie, where he decided by that time he had three or four children.
And he decided that railroading wasn't for a family man.
And he quit his railroading and set up a general store.
We'd call it a general mercantile store today.
He sold everything from coffee and beans and sugar to harnesses and buggies and whips and plows and this kind of thing.
And where did he set that up?
In Waukesha Hatchie.
Oh, I see.
That's where he quit railroading.
And the railroad went on into Fort Worth, but he quit in Waukesha Hatchie and set up his general mercantile store there.
Well, as such, he
He would trade a plow for a cow or trade a bedroom suit for so many chickens or a calf or something.
He made a good living for his wife and living kids.
He remembered his young college student in Hamburg, Germany.
of the Heine Boiler Company there.
And something motivated him to contact them when he had this general mercantile store there in Waukesha Hatchie to get the Heine Boiler franchise for Texas.
And he did that.
And that motivated him after he found that he could make more money out of selling and installing boilers than he could out of his mercantile store, he moved to Dallas.
And he sold lots of boilers around, Heine boilers.
They were a very efficient coal-fired boiler in those days.
I know of two of them that still have his name, or did have his name plates on them a year or so ago.
One that he put in at White Rock Water Pump Station.
and one down at the old Brown Cracker and Candy Company down on Lamar Street.
He installed and sold them and installed them, and I'm sure there were many, many more around town and in Texas.
He made a good living out of it and made some money.
And after the war, I mean after he got too old to work,
He retired, of course, and wrote his memoirs of the Civil War.
Really?
I've got a copy here.
No kidding.
It was a great thing for the old gentleman.
He spent a lot of time doing that.
I bet you really enjoyed this.
Oh, yeah.
And he reached the rank of general.
No, no, no, no.
That is after the war in the United Confederate Veterans Organization.
Oh, I see.
Like reserves are today.
He was commissary general, which means quartermaster general today.
Oh, this is fantastic.
1916, this is published.
Well, I've sat on his knee by the hour and by the day, and he tells me all the tales are here and there, and this is a real trophy, a real... Sure is.
Heirloom.
What impact do you think he had on your mother?
Well, certainly he was a stern disciplinarian,
In his own right, that was the way he was brought up.
And he was with my mother and all the kids and with me, with my brother and me when we came along.
He was a distinguished gentleman, very patient, very kind old gentleman.
I'm sure he was a tremendous influence on my family.
Was your father the authority in the household then?
You bet.
You bet he was.
My daddy was very patient with my brother and me.
My brother's 20 months older than I am.
And of course, growing up like kids will do, we had our differences.
Oh, sure.
And we're always at one another's trying to excel in one another.
Every now and then, we'd get beyond our better judgments, and we'd go to Fish City.
And Mama would tell him about it as soon as we got home.
And boy, I'd go to the woodshed.
That's all there was to it.
Went to the woodshed, and he impressed on us.
I wasn't worried for his boys to act.
The last lick he and I got was for, I'll never forget,
I was always taught to say yes ma'am and no ma'am, yes sir and no sir to anybody who's older than I am.
And I do it today.
But one time my mother said something to me, I don't know, I was sure I, I doubt if I, I was probably in grammar school, but not much, never very far in grammar school.
And mama asked me a question and I said no or yes, one, I forget which.
And she told Eddie when he came home from work, hey, boy, go to the woodshed.
I went to the woodshed, and he came out and talked to me for 10 minutes, telling me that wasn't the way for young boys to grow up, and it wasn't the way he wanted his children to react.
And then he got his belt off, and he was impressing me with that.
And he broke his belt on me.
Really?
It was probably an old belt.
A leather belt?
Huh?
A leather belt?
Oh, yeah.
It was an old leather belt, probably rotten.
And I may have had a grin on my face when he broke that belt because he said, boy, you stay there.
And he went back in the house.
He saved with one of these old fashioned razors.
It had a long razor strap like he used to be home.
And he brought that razor strap out there.
And he got my attention with that razor strap.
That's what he did.
And today I say yes sir, no sir, no ma'am, and yes ma'am to any lady and to anybody that's older than I am.
That's one of the indelible things that I learned.
It didn't hurt me a bit in the world.
It taught me a lesson.
I live by the day.
Treat your brother the same way?
You bet.
How many brothers did you have?
Just two?
Just the two of us.
Two kids in the family?
Just the two of us, yeah.
Oh, yeah.
He was a very stern person, meaning he'd tell you to do something, and he'd tell you why he wanted it done that way.
Like eating at the table.
He'd say, I don't care how much you take.
You take three pieces of chicken or four pieces of chicken.
Take all the chicken.
But you can eat what's on your plate.
because we can't afford to waste it.
And he didn't have to say, boy, what's on the plate, put twice to me.
First time, he said it, and I didn't eat it.
And the second time, he said it, and he wham, and I ended in the corner.
And today, I don't take anything and put it on the plate.
I don't eat.
I clean my plate up.
But he was a great person.
I mean, he indulged kids.
He indulged me in the wind.
and sending me to the Hawaii schools and Hawaii camps.
He indulged us by buying me a new baseball mitt when my mitt was old and rotted out where I left it out in the rain and it got rotted.
He would go play with us on Saturday afternoon or Sunday, play ball with all the kids in the neighborhood.
And so for all of his strict discipline, he was a great leader for kids, is what I'm trying to say.
And all the kids in the neighborhood respect him, and certainly I do.
I did then, and I knew now.
I don't remember crossing him twice, and that was the time when I said, yeah, not to my mother, and when I didn't eat what was on my plate.
And he told me the first time, the second time, why he didn't.
He told me another way, and I respect it.
Now, it sounds like he had a definite impact on your career.
No question about it.
In what way do you think he helped you to succeed?
Well, he taught me to think straight and sit down and reason and convince myself that what I was doing is right, and then to follow through on it if it's right.

at that particular time is right today you know situations change and that changes your your decision but if you sit down and reason the thing out with the best information you have at the time that's right right thing to do at that time why that's the right thing to do period and that's the way i've always lived that's where
worked in my Army career, and that's where I ran my business, and that's where I live today.
Okay, let's talk about your education.
We haven't touched on that.
Could you tell me about that?
Well, I started in, we lived on the corner of Ross and Fitcher, where I was born, and right across the street from it, Caddy Wompert Cross Street, is Fannin Grade School, which is still there.
And that's where I went to grammar school, grade school, we called it in those days.
I remember one event that happened.
It was a two-story building.
They had a square block, and the grade school sat back in the far end of the block there, away from our house.
And I remember it caught on fire one night, in retrospect, and hearing all the discussion and everything, and the arsonist set it on fire.
an arsonist who wanted to get even with his girlfriend, who was a teacher there.
Of course, I remember this back and hearing my parents talk about it.
But anyway, when the fire engines came and they started putting the fire out and all, my mother and my father looked for me in the bed, and I wasn't there.
So they knew exactly where I was.
And when they got in there looking for me, they tell me the story that there I was tugging on the fireman's coat.
Please, Mr. Fireman, let it burn a little more so I won't have to go to school tomorrow.
But I went there.
In other words, would it be fair to say that you did not like grade school?
No, this typical kid reaction would burn the school down.
No, I loved school.
I loved to be with the kids, and I tried to...
excelled in school.
My daddy and my uncle encouraged my brother and me both to excel.
And they had an incentive program between them.
Wanted to do it one year and wanted to do it the next year.
Offering us
and I think it started out in nickel and E. In those days, they grade you excellent, E for excellent, an S for satisfactory, a P for passion, and a U for unsatisfactory.
And my father would give my brother or me
a nickel for each E we'd bring home.
And he wouldn't give us anything but a frown and say, boy, do better when we brought home an S or a P. I remember specifically he says, don't bring any U's home.
And I knew that about- You'd never bring any home?
I knew enough by that time not to bring any home.
No, I didn't.
Not until I got to A&M.
I started grammar school in 1917 and graduated in 1924, of course, seven years of grammar school.
I went over to North Dallas in 1924 and graduated in 1928.
What were your favorite subjects?
I just took a straight course in high school with the idea of going to A&M and studying engineering, meaning I took four years of mathematics, four years of English, four years of Latin.
I don't know why I took Latin except I had a little girlfriend who was studying Latin, so
That may have had some influence on me.
I've often said I should have taken four years of Spanish, but I didn't.
And then took the real usual subjects of chemistry and physics and some extra mathematics, extra algebra, and an indoctrination course in calculus and that kind of thing.
You said that you had the idea that you were going to go to A&M to study engineering.
When did you get this idea?
When you were 13, 14, 15 years old?
I presume it was about that formerly age.
How'd you come about this idea?
Well, I had a cousin that I admired, and he went to A&M.
Oh, I see.
And he would come home at Christmas time or during the summer, and he impressed me.
that was place to go to be an engineer and I had wanted to be an engineer.
I've always loved to build things and my cousin going down there and he'd come home in his uniform and that impressed me and when I got in high school I
decided to take ROTC and that's where I wanted to go to A&M.
And I set my heart on it and that's where my family and I were able to swing the deal.
Would you consider yourself a leader in high school in any way?
Did you organize any groups?
or activities or sports or anything?
Well, yes, I played at sports.
I never did really excel in sports.
Perhaps I didn't apply myself to it because I had the size and all, but it was more fun instead of trying to excel in it.
It's highly motivated today, and to me it was just a
relaxation and another something for me to do in my spare time.
I was interested in having an academic status rather than a physical sports status.
I set my heart on being an engineer and my father and even my cousin who graduated down there or
who had been down there impressed on me that you had to apply yourself and study.
And that sold me on going to A&M.
And that's what directed me just taking the standard four-year course in high school of four years math, four years English.
four years Latin, and actually I learned more English in Latin class than I did in English class.
I think that's fine basic instruction for any youngster coming along, if he can work it in his curriculum, and I did.
So when you graduated from high school then, you had a firm set of goals or aims that you already wanted to accomplish.
Yes, I had made up my mind I wanted to be an engineer.
Now why was that?
During the summers I worked in, my cousin first.
And during the summers I had worked on construction jobs as a water boy first, and then as a timekeeper, and then as a kind of a office boy.
running errands for the superintendent, or going and getting some equipment, or going and getting some material, or this kind of thing.
And I wanted to be an engineer.
I wanted the engineering training, ultimately, to get into the construction business for myself.
And so I planted that seed back in those days and finally germinated in 1952.
when I set up this company.
Actually I had a partner but that lasted for a while and then I bought him out and I ran it from 1964.
That's when I bought him out and I've run it ever since until July 1st last year when I sold it.
Tell me about your first impressions of A&M.
Well, it's any good, bad, and any different.
My first impression of A&M is that my father and my mother put me on a train.
The old Lyle had used to leave Dallas at 11.30 at night and got down to College Station about 4.30 in the morning.
And they packed me up with a suitcase,
And I guess a footlocker, something like that.
Put me on the train and wished me well.
And I got off this train down at the old station, which sat across, is that Highway 5 or Highway 6 runs up and down there?
And that was between the railroad station and the campus, the old main academic building, which was the campus.
They had that esplanade with the lights going up there.
And got off and got off the train and of course nobody knew anything about where to go, what you do.
And it was some enterprise, some sophomore down there, selling brooms and this kind of thing too.
you need a broom sweep your room out and all that kind of thing.

And it seemed like I walked a hundred miles getting up to the academic building where A&M had some person in authority and said you make yourselves at home and this is where you want to be at eight o'clock and we'll matriculate and go from there.

and uh he said you can carry did you carry that big case oh no i carried my suitcase but i didn't carry the footlocker i just just left that down there it was it was baggage so to speak and they unloaded all that on the loading docks and i went down there after i found out i was going to live in goodman hall this gentleman admitted us also said you can walk right down this way
that big, long building down there, which is a piece of hall, and you can get something to eat if you're hungry.
So when the sun came up, a bunch of us said, let's go get something to eat.
And we went and got something to eat, waiting until 8 o'clock came when the advisors got out and told us how to go about matriculating.
And we took our choice of what branch of the service we wanted to be in.
And there were three of us from North Dallas High School that went down.
I'd always loved to ride horses in my younger days.
And so as an engineering student, we had the choice of being in the engineers or the field artillery.
And I chose field artillery.
And these other two boys wanted to go into the cavalry, but I persuaded them.
we all three went in the field artillery.
And that's where I started in the field artillery and training and of course it stayed right with me until I retired.
I was one of the very fortunate field artillerymen to be able to have trained all the way through from an old French 75 through the
horse-drawn artillery and through the motorized artillery and through the rocket artillery up to the Zeus and Nike, which is where I left them.
And that was a very fortunate day, a complete cycle of military armament from a pea shooter up to the rockets as we know them today.
Yeah, a revolution.
A real revolution.
Just like we've had the machine revolution and the social revolution, there was a real revolution in hardware in the Army.

Now let's talk about A&M for a minute here, and what I'd like to know is did the military, the aspect that A&M was a military institution, did that have anything to do with your decision, or when did you first become interested in the military?
When I went to high school, I joined the ROTC there.
And I continually worked at it, meaning I participated in all the events, meaning they had the crack company, which was a
represented North Dallas High School in competition against the other four high schools at that time, the other three high schools at that time.
They only had four high schools in Dallas in those days.
And we had rifle competition.
Margin and drill competition?
Drill competition, purely and simply drill competition as a company unit.
Right.
We won it one year and we got beat three years and win some, lose some, you know.
What did you like about down?
Well, I love the artillery.
I love the competition in it.
I said artillery, I mean the drill.
I love the drill and the competition in it.
And because I worked at it, I got

promoted to corporal, and then sergeant, and then six striper, sergeant major, and then I don't know, I guess my junior year I got promoted to lieutenant, and my senior year I was promoted to captain, and the company commander, which was up the line, you know.
I participated in the rifles competition, the pistol competition,
And we participated in horse competitions.
We were using the old 112th Cavalry, which National Guard troop horses.
Our commandant over in North Dallas had a friend that commanded one of the troops in the 112th Cavalry.
And he would let us come out and exercise the horses on Saturday, meaning that we could ride them and run them.
And that was a real fun and a real challenge.
And that confirmed my love for horses and it eventually showed up in the artillery.
Yeah.
So in other words, you had a position of leadership as early as high school in the military.
Yes, I was a company commander and
I commanded the crack company, but we didn't win the competition.
But I'm sure I'll lose some of this, I don't know what to say about that.
Sure, oh yeah.
Tell me about your, when you got to A&M and you were on the Aggie Corps, could you tell me about your outfit?
Well, I was in B battery field artillery the whole time.
I started over there in Goodwin Hall.
We lived two years in Goodwin, one year in Milner, and one year in Mitchell Halls.
I don't know whether Goodwin's still there or not.
I think it is, yeah.
Milner and Mitchell are still there.
I think they've renovated those, but I don't know about Goodwin.
There was Goodwin, and right behind it is the Zell Hall, and then the
chapel was on down at the end of the military old drag there, the old chapel where we went to church.
I rocked along and made average grades.
I didn't excel because I was having fishitis, I guess you'd call it.
They don't participate in that type of hazing anymore, but they sure did in my era.
Well, can you tell me about some of the experiences, those hazing experiences?

Well, at this upperclassmen-run company, company commander is a senior, of course, and he ran it, and he delegated his authority to the first sergeant, and the first sergeant ran the housekeeping of it, and sophomores did all the
the hazing, so to speak, and being sophomores and making the freshmen adhere to their likings and dislikings.
It's all good fun.
It was a typical A&M tradition.
And I don't regret one moment of it.
I say that the change has been all for the better.
Perhaps it was excessive in my day, but I don't begrudge it.
Every sophomore and junior and one or two seniors that whipped my ass, I respected tremendously because they were my seniors.
And sometimes I didn't clean their room like they thought I ought to.
I was reprimanded for it, but that was part of the fun of being a freshman, a fish.
I don't think it hurt me a bit, and it certainly, I think, made a better man of being able to take punishment and liking it.
And every time that
One of them whipped my ass.
I got up and thanked him for it, for straightening me out.
And that was the tradition of A&M at that time.
And these gentlemen who you're talking to will tell you the same story.
Yeah, I know.
It's just interesting.
It was a tradition in those days.
And if you stayed past the first Thanksgiving, why, you could live with anything.
People that were completely obsessed with going to A&M and participating in the core traditions didn't come back after Thanksgiving.
Or certainly they didn't come back after Christmas, the first year.
And if you stayed that first four months, five months, the only reason you left A&M was because of
academic deficiency.
Did a lot of people drop out?
Because of what now?
Because of the hazing?
Did a lot of your colleagues say, well, I just don't want to take this?
Do you remember?
Well, I'm sure some of them did.
I'm sure some of them did.
My two roommates dropped out at
One of them dropped out at the end of our fish year because of academic deficiency.
They wouldn't let him return.
And the other one dropped out at the end of my sophomore year because of financial considerations.
I doubt if 10% of them dropped out because of this so-called hazing.
I doubt it because
Then a boy didn't go down there unless he was obsessed with wanting to go to A&M and wanting to be in the Corps.
You had to be in the Corps to go there.
Or you were classified as a casual, meaning you had a physical disability and you had to wear a uniform at that.
But if you had a physical disability, well, you could go be a casual, but you
wore the uniform.
So everybody was in uniform, everybody was the same.
Rich men, poor men, sons are all the same.
And the only thing that separates you was your academic leadership or qualifications and your ROTC.
Did you like the fact that you were all the same?
Did I like the fact?
You bet.
You bet because
Those were hard times.
Sure were.
Those were hard times.
And I'm sure there were some rich men's sons there.
But my father wasn't a rich man.
And he had two of us in college at the same time.
And my brother went to University of Texas.
And I was A&M.
And so I worked while I was down there.
Can you tell me what you did?
I worked.
doing everything, anything I could get a job at doing.
I worked in Spesa Hall.
I worked building help as labor on Saturdays, helped building the then chemistry building, the new chemistry building, and I'm sure it's been enlarged many times since then.
Dr. Hedges was the
head of the chemistry department at that time.
I worked over there as a laborer.
I worked down in the agronomy lab grinding up samples of dirt and running tests for old Dr. Asbury, who was one of the old great saints of A&M at that time.
Do you remember what you made?
As I remember,
15 cents an hour.
